5.body: For documentation on the input/output of the API Caller functions, please reference their respective Lambda Functions below. In the following table, the function name links to its source code definition, and the Lambda name links to its documentation. Function Name Corresponding Lambda Function Description NOT DEFINED YET getAccountMeals TO DO getCategoryInfo getCategoryInfo Returns category name, image given ID getExplorePage getExplorePage Gets a host of information to be displayed on the explore page getFullMealInfo getFullMealInfo Gets, at present, the method steps for a meal getMealsInCategories getMealsInCategories Gets all meals that match a list of categories, sorted into recommended order getMealInfo getMealInfo Gets all information about a meal to be displayed on small card getNeptuneUserInfo getNeptuneUserInfo Gets info about a user (allergens, preferences etc) getQMSearch getQMSearch Get list of meal IDs that match a QuickMeals search
5.title: Available Functions

54.body:
When providing data to create a new meal, it must be in the following format: data = { // Below values generated by Gremlin: id: INT, // Unique ID added by Gremlin label: 'meal', // Added by Gremlin // Below values specified by us: name: "Meal #1", allergens: [INT, ...], // List of allergens (represented by codes) categories: [INT, ...], // List of category codes ingredients: [INT, ...] // List of ingredient codes.
} // All numerical codes will be the same as the ID of that entity in DynamoDB.
54.title: Meal Nodes

55.body:
When providing data to create a new user node, it must be in the following format: data = { // Below values generated by Gremlin: id: INT, // Unique ID added by Gremlin label: 'user', // Added by Gremlin // Below values specified by us: allergens: [INT, ...], // List of user's allergens. preferences: [INT, ...], // List of categories that a user likes. (E.g vegan, mexican) dislikedIngredients: [INT, ...], // List of ingredients that user dislikes. dislikedCategories: [INT, ...] // List of category codes that a user dislikes.
}
55.title: User Nodes

65.body: What is S3? Simply put, S3 (Simple Storage Service) is an object storage service in the cloud. IMPORTANT: NOT A DATABASE Storage in S3 Storage in S3 is not structured, and is considered a data lake where data is stored in a single file Note: files and paths are for UI ease of use only
65.title: S3 Overview

66.body: Bucket Folders Keys Metadata Session, Features Session: users/${userID}/sessions/${sessionID}, Features: users/${userID}/features/${feature}/${sessionID} Content Images, Main_Content, Method Images: Image_${MealId}, Main_Content: Main_Content_${MealId}, Method: Method_${MealId}
66.breadcrumbs: Backend » S3 » Our S3 Storage Structure
66.title: Our S3 Storage Structure

68.body:
{ "mealName": STRING, "servings": INT, "prepTime": { "time": INT, "unit": STR // E.g "min", "hr" }, "cookTime": { "time": INT, "unit": STR }, "tags": [STRING], // E.g "Vegan", "Healthy". "ingredientsText": { // Ingredients separated into their uses "Ingredients": [STRING], // E.g "150g baby spinach" "For the falafel": [...], "SECTION_NAME": [...] // Ingredients in "Ingredients" section are not duplicated in the subsequent subsections }, "ingredients": [INT], // List of ingredient IDs "method": [STRING] // List of instructions
}
